Ukraine", "description": "Russian President Vladimir Putin and US President Joe Biden spoke again on the phone Thursday afternoon about Ukraine. Russia requested the call, according to The New York Times. Per the White House, Putin and Biden spoke for about 50 minutes. The leaders last call that was made known to the public was on December 7, when Russia said it would send ideas on the crisis to Washington "within a week," Reuters reported. The US Air Force flew two reconnaissance missions over eastern Ukraine this week, the first on December 27 just a few days after Russia said it would withdraw 10,000 troops from the shared border, CNN reported.

More on the leaders’ call:
- Ukraine has been a point of contention for the two countries since the annexation of Crimea in 2014, Al Jazeera reports

- Russia denied a new assault on Ukraine during the previous conversation and warned against any NATO military involvement, according to Reuters and Al Jazeera

- Biden warned Putin about possible sanctions against Russia in case of an escalation during the December 7 call, AFP reports"}}, {"domain": {"id": "29", "name": "Events [Entity Service]", "description": "Entity Service related Events domain"}, "entity": {"id": "1483255084750282753", "name": "Latest updates on the war in Ukraine", "description": "On February 24, Russia launched an invasion of Ukraine by land, air and sea after months of tensions between Moscow and Kyiv. Tens of thousands have lost their lives and 5.3 million people have been forced to flee their homes, the greatest refugee surge to OECD countries since World War II. Keep it here for the latest on-the-ground updates.

Ukraine", "description": "Russian President Vladimir Putin and US President Joe Biden spoke again on the phone Thursday afternoon about Ukraine. Russia requested the call, according to The New York Times. Per the White House, Putin and Biden spoke for about 50 minutes. The leaders last call that was made known to the public was on December 7, when Russia said it would send ideas on the crisis to Washington "within a week," Reuters reported. The US Air Force flew two reconnaissance missions over eastern Ukraine this week, the first on December 27 just a few days after Russia said it would withdraw 10,000 troops from the shared border, CNN reported.

More on the leaders’ call:
- Ukraine has been a point of contention for the two countries since the annexation of Crimea in 2014, Al Jazeera reports

- Russia denied a new assault on Ukraine during the previous conversation and warned against any NATO military involvement, according to Reuters and Al Jazeera

- Biden warned Putin about possible sanctions against Russia in case of an escalation during the December 7 call, AFP reports"}}, {"domain": {"id": "29", "name": "Events [Entity Service]", "description": "Entity Service related Events domain"}, "entity": {"id": "1483255084750282753", "name": "Latest updates on the war in Ukraine", "description": "On February 24, Russia launched an invasion of Ukraine by land, air and sea after months of tensions between Moscow and Kyiv. The US Air Force flew two reconnaissance missions over eastern Ukraine this week, the first on December 27 just a few days after Russia said it would withdraw 10,000 troops from the shared border, CNN reported.

- Ukraine has been a point of contention for the two countries since the annexation of Crimea in 2014, Al Jazeera reports

2. Total mobilisation in remote rural regions, especially ethnic ones

and US President Joe Biden spoke again on the phone Thursday afternoon about Ukraine. Russia requested the call, according to The New York Times. Per the White House, Putin and Biden spoke for about 50 minutes. The leaders last call that was made known to the public was on December 7, when Russia said it would send ideas on the crisis to Washington "within a week," Reuters reported. The US Air Force flew two reconnaissance missions over eastern Ukraine this week, the first on December 27 just a few days after Russia said it would withdraw 10,000 troops from the shared border, CNN reported.
